Based on the search results, here's what I found about defining custom CSS variables for colors in Tailwind CSS v4 using the `@theme` directive:

## Basic Color Definition with @theme

In Tailwind CSS v4, theme variables are special CSS variables defined using the @theme directive that influence which utility classes exist in your project. For example, you can add a new color to your project by defining a theme variable like --color-mint-500.

Here's a basic example:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  --color-primary: #aab9ff;
  --color-secondary: #56d0a0;
  --color-mint-500: oklch(68% 0.1 250);
}
```

CSS variables that have the namespace --color-* will be used to generate new color utility classes. This means you can then use classes like `bg-primary`, `text-secondary`, or `bg-mint-500` in your HTML.

## Multi-Theme Strategy

Tailwind CSS v4 drastically simplifies the process of defining themable CSS variables:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme {
  --color-primary: #aab9ff;
}

@layer base {
  [data-theme='ocean'] {
    --color-primary: #aab9ff;
  }
  [data-theme='rainforest'] {
    --color-primary: #56d0a0;
  }
  [data-theme='candy'] {
    --color-primary: #f9a8d4;
  }
}
```

## Using @theme with Regular CSS Variables

For more complex theming scenarios, you can use @theme inline with references to other CSS variables:

```css
@import "tailwindcss";

@theme inline {
  --color-primary: var(--primary);
}

@layer base {
  :root {
    --primary: red;
  }
  .blue {
    --primary: blue;
  }
}
```

Use @theme when you want a design token to map directly to a utility class, and use :root for defining regular CSS variables that shouldn't have corresponding utility classes.


